Linux Fundamentals
This section builds on core Linux usage, focusing on file operations, text processing, permissions, users/groups, environment variables, shells, and standard streams.

1. File & Directory Navigation
Basic Commands
cd – change directory
cd .. – move up one directory
cd / – go to the root directory
ls – list directory contents
ls -a – include hidden files
ls -l – long listing with permissions
ls -la – long listing including hidden files

2. File Creation & Viewing
Creating Files
touch file.txt – create an empty file
vim file.txt – create/edit a file (creates if it doesn’t exist)
Viewing File Contents
cat file.txt – display file contents
head file.txt – first 10 lines
head -n 5 file.txt – first 5 lines
tail file.txt – last 10 lines
tail -n 3 file.txt – last 3 lines
Pipelines
head -n 10 file.txt | tail -n 5
Takes the first 10 lines, then outputs the last 5 of those
| (pipe) passes output of one command to another

3. Writing & Combining Files
Redirecting Output
echo "hello" > file.txt – overwrite file
echo "new line" >> file.txt – append to file
Combining Files
cat file1.txt file2.txt > combined.txt – combine into new file
cat file1.txt >> file2.txt – append contents of one file to another

4. Copying, Moving & Deleting
Copy
cp file.txt file_copy.txt – copy file
cp -r my_directory my_directory_copy – copy directory recursively
Move / Rename
mv file.txt backup.txt – rename file
mv file.txt my_directory/ – move file into directory
Delete
rm file.txt – delete file
rm -r my_directory – delete directory recursively
⚠️ Dangerous Command
rm -rf / – forcefully deletes the entire system (DO NOT RUN)

5. Programs, Binaries & PATH
Programs: Written by developers to perform tasks
Binaries: Compiled versions of programs
How Commands Work
Shell interprets command
Searches directories listed in $PATH
Executes the binary
PATH Environment Variable
Contains directories where executables live (e.g. /bin, /sbin)
echo $PATH – display PATH value

6. Vim Editor Basics
Modes
Command mode – default
Insert mode – press i
Visual mode – press v
Press Esc to return to command mode
Saving & Exiting
:wq – save and quit
:q! – quit without saving
Navigation (Command Mode)
h – left
l – right
j – down
k – up
:4 – jump to line 4
Editing
dd – delete entire line
D – delete from cursor to end of line
y – yank (copy)
p – paste
u – undo
Ctrl + r – redo
Search
/example – search for word
n – next result
N – previous result
Extras
:set number – show line numbers
:set nonumber – hide line numbers
:syntax on – enable syntax highlighting

